reviewText: Missed this show on PBS, so I went on Amazon and purchased it.  Pretty good piece on a subject of military history that is generally ignored by most.  I just wish there would have been some information about the early years and how it all got started.  Other than that I found the show to be very well crafted and entertaining.  If you have room in your collection and enjoy military history. I would add this one.
This is the best SEAL video explaining The inns and outs of the Navy SEALs. My father was a part of the first evolution of the seals and says it's pretty close to how the teams came together.

Purchased so my father, an old Navy Seal, could watch it. He thought it was good, seemed accurate to him. He was UDT1 during Korean War, recognized some of the footage.

An excellent film, The history of the seals from their military beginning was wonderful. Starting with being a demolition crew, was amazing, since they protected the military ships from underwater bombs, and military barges landing on the beach were protected from enemy traps set up on the beach.  The SEALS did some much to protect the American troops when they landed on the beach during the invasion of Normande, the largest military invasion in history.  An incredible group of men, who are specialized in military combat on land, sea, and air.  What great courage these men have.  This is a must see film for the special men of Seal team  6. who SO often are not know by the public for all that they do.

Gives a person a whole new set of pride of why our military do what they do behind the public eyes. Makes you love and appreciate
the Office of President and those whom are working to provide a safe place for not only Americans but others in our world and the cost it truly has been and the heros whom no one ever knew was working to make things happen to provide safety for other military persons as well as those whom do not have any idea as to what is going on against the USA in the shadows they do not know of.

My boys, ages 7 and 6, are intrigued by all things military.  This was a very informative and interesting history of the SEALs.  The documentary is well-paced and doesn't get dry or "boring." It has photos and video footage from WWII as well as interviews with former SEALs. I was busy working on the computer while the boys were watching it and I found myself paying more attention to the documentary than I was to my work. This kept the boys riveted, even my 3 1/2 year old twins. Several days after watching it, the boys wanted to watch it again.  This is good enough that I will probably end up buying it. If you are interested in military this is an excellent documentary.  I'm not big into war movies- and even I enjoyed watching this.

I'm not sure if the subject material just causes it to appear that way, if the military funded this, or if it is the only way to get participation from the military in making these.

Whatever the case, if you don't mind having the stories presented to you in such a way as to always present the Navy Seals as the good guys, this isn't a bad film to watch.  But if you have been a fan of military documentaries over the past 15 years or so you may not get anything new from it.

CAPTIVATING DOCUMENTARY

This documentary on the history of the US Navy SEALs is absolutely captivating. It goes back further than the actual Trident wearing SEALs of the modern era, back to their predecessors in World War II, showing the groundwork that was laid to create the modern day SEALs.

I was riveted for this entire 2 hour show. It presents the facts of the history in a way that makes it very easy to understand the military need and global political climate and how those two things worked together to create a use for SEAL teams. And its all very easy to follow and understand.

I found this on Amazon instant video and gave it a try....and am I glad I did. What an amazing documentary. I learned so much about the history of Navy Frogmen, and was highly entertained by the education the entire time.

As a Marine I have worked with SEALs in training ops and the level of dedication these guys bring to the table is surreal. It's awesome to see the history of the teams back to their inception, which is largely overlooked in all the modern day coverage of what SEALs are doing right now.

Any military history fan would love this.

This is not a profession that anyone just gets into it just for the heck of it since it requires certain qualifications. The first and foremost, one needs to be genetically fit to tolerate all the mental as well as physical pressures since there is so much diet and activity can do when it comes to being fit. Secondly, it requires determination. I am into health, nutrition and many sports and there is not a single session of any type of work out that I go through that I can feel satisfied unless I am alert and I know that I have to push and push regardless if it is mountain biking, hiking, surfing, pumping iron or whatever since not only human body is designed to be lazy but more importantly as we age, our capabilities become limited so determination is the biggest motivation of all except that there are so many rewarding moments of satisfaction where it comes with those kind of activities.

With all that said, it is not difficult to understand that the only reason why anyone would want to be a Navy Seals --that is only if one qualifies-- would be nothing other than being the best of best when it comes to many tasks requiring many human capabilities which comes with personal rewards and satisfactions not for fame, otherwise Olympics would be a better option. For those reasons it was very confusing to me watching few top Navy Seals going public on CBS 60 Minutes, disguising themselves and talking about their accomplishments when I assumed that just being able to be in that group and accomplishing those tasks when trusted would have been the biggest gift of all for personal reasons.

This is not a documentary about the Seals only, it is more, much more. It covers two hours of America's history. There is so much to learn that they should show this documentary in every school so Americans can understand what war means and what it takes to be on top of the game when it comes in winning a war, any type of war, anywhere. Seals are true Americans who put everything they have got on line while most citizens have no idea of what givings means unless they know of them.
